<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-06-12T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-06-12T02:00:00-05:00" n="593" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d593">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">761.6215/18: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Thurston</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-12T10:00:00+03:00">June 12,
                                    1940—10 a.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received June 12—7:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>663. Embassy’s telegram No. 466, April 27, 5 p.m.<note n="11" xml:id="d593fn11">Not printed.</note> The Embassy has been informed
                            by a Secretary of the German Embassy that the Soviet and German
                            Governments have concluded a treaty for the regulation of border
                                disputes.<note n="12" xml:id="d593fn12">Signed at Moscow on June 10,
                                1940.</note> The informant indicated that the treaty was of purely
                            technical nature and of no political significance. He added that it
                            contained provision for the settlement of border disputes by the local
                            frontier authorities.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Thurston</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>